- Implement a custom hook `useDebouncedSave`:
  ```ts
  function useDebouncedSave<T>(value: T, delay: number, onSave: (value: T) => void) {
    const [status, setStatus] = useState<"idle" | "saving" | "saved">("idle");
    useEffect(() => {
      if (!onSave) return;
      setStatus("saving");
      const handler = setTimeout(() => {
        onSave(value);
        setStatus("saved");
        const timeout = setTimeout(() => setStatus("idle"), 1000);
        return () => clearTimeout(timeout);
      }, delay);
      return () => clearTimeout(handler);
    }, [value, delay, onSave]);
    return status;
  }
  ```
- Integrate into `BriefBuilder` or parent container, depending on architecture:
  - Option A: `BriefBuilder` receives an optional `onAutoSave` prop; if provided, wrap `briefData` changes and pass into `useDebouncedSave`.
  - Option B: Provide only hook and example usage so the hosting app wires persistence.
- Display a small status indicator near the top-right of the User View (and optionally other views):
  - "Saving..." when status is `saving`.
  - "Saved" when status is `saved`.
  - Hidden or subtle icon when `idle`.
- Ensure auto-save is non-blocking; it should not affect validation or user navigation.
- Use a reasonable default debounce delay (e.g., 500–1000 ms) and allow override via prop if needed.
